Ancient China (2100 BCE - 221 CE):

* The Xia Dynasty (c. 2100 - 1600 BCE) was the first known Chinese dynasty. It was followed by the Shang Dynasty (c. 1600 - 1046 BCE), which introduced writing and the use of bronze for tools and weapons.
* The Zhou Dynasty (c. 1046 - 256 BCE) saw the rise of feudalism and the development of Confucian philosophy.
* The Qin Dynasty (221 - 206 BCE) unified China for the first time under one ruler, Shi Huangdi, who created the Great Wall of China.

Imperial China (206 BCE - 1912 CE):

* The Han Dynasty (206 BCE - 220 CE) marked a period of economic growth, cultural exchange with other civilizations, and the invention of paper.
* The Tang Dynasty (618 - 907 CE) saw a golden age of culture, art, and religion, with influences from Buddhism and Taoism.
* The Ming Dynasty (1368 - 1644 CE) saw the construction of the Forbidden City and the Great Wall of China, as well as the creation of the Chinese calendar and the development of porcelain production.
* The Qing Dynasty (1644 - 1912 CE) was the last imperial dynasty, marked by conflict with Western powers and the Opium Wars.

Modern China (1912 CE - present):

* The fall of the Qing Dynasty led to the establishment of the Republic of China in 1912.
* In 1949, the Communist Party of China took control of the country, marking the beginning of the People's Republic of China.
* Under Mao Zedong's leadership, China experienced significant social and economic changes, including land reform, industrialization, and collectivization.
* Since Mao's death in 1976, China has continued to open up to the world economy and adopt market-oriented reforms, leading to rapid economic growth and increased global influence.

